text: <p>"This patient has a known diagnosis of metastatic ovarian carcinoma, having presented initially with a huge pelvic mass. The mass is visible on this PFA as a large soft tissue density structure extending into the abdomen from the pelvis, arrows. Note the displaced bowel loops. There are bilateral nephrostomy catheters, as the pelvic mass had obstructed both ureters."</p>

<p><img alt="Duodenal Atresia | Pediatric Radiology Reference Article | Pediatric  Imaging | @pedsimaging" src="https://pediatricimaging.files.wordpress.com/2019/02/duodenalatresia01jakaxrsupupsq.jpg" />This patient has a duodenal atresia, which presents on an abdominal X-ray as a "double-bubble" sign (the black bubbles seen on the image).</p>
<p>Is this the double bubble sign seen with duodenal atresia? </p>
<p>Wow, this is really interesting. I didn't expect an ovarian tumor to look like this on x-ray.</p>
<p>I haven't seen a double bubble sign before on x-ray, but this is super interesting.</p>
<p>Is this only a congenital condition or can it happen at any time?</p>
<p>This is the Sentinel Loop Sign!  "Abdominal radiography showing dilated loops of small bowel, in a patient with an acute pancreatitis."</p>
<p>It was interesting to see the nephrostomy catheters as well, and how they appear on imaging!</p>
<p>A lot of the other x-rays I have seen have had some bubbles, but these seem bigger than any I've scrolled through so far!</p>
<p>I also thought this looked similar to the double-bubble sign. I wonder how similar they are and how you tell the difference between them.</p>

<p>Normal pregnancy (23 weeks gestation) on CT following motor vehicle accident (sustained lower limb fractures). Though usually not ideal for pregnant people to get CTs done, the need to check for severe injuries following a notable accident outweighs the relatively tiny risk that it poses to the fetus.</p>

<p>I am interested to know what caused this. I can't tell if the fuzziness is impacted bowel or not, but there's also the pockets of air (or blood) and something about the ribs looks odd to me but I can't place much. Was it a blunt trauma cause? </p>
<p>It's really interesting to see how medical devices appear on these images. Do you know what that dot/target shaped thing is in the upper left below the (10th?) rib? </p>

<p>This patient is a 25yo male presenting with RLQ pain and tenderness. Though this may be an obvious diagnosis, it's still really interesting to see it on the CT scan. This website provides an axial view, and coronal view. </p>

<p>This is really interesting because I remember being told as a kid that swallowing magnets was particularly dangerous. I looked up why, and the damage is largely caused because magnets can come together in through loops of intestine and cause bowel perforations. Additionally, the magnets can block part of the intestine and cause an obstruction and even necrosis. </p>

<p>It's so cool to see the shift of the organs during pregnancy! I wonder if the organs go back to normal after birth or always are slightly displaced. Also- I wonder if all the black spaces are air or if it's normal spaces in the peritoneal cavity due to pregnancy? </p>

<p>Courtesy of the American Journal of Roengenology, this is an image of a child with a rare condition called pseudo-prune belly syndrome. It is similar in presentation to prune belly syndrome, which is abdominal distention caused by hypoplasia of abdominal musculature, though this conditions is not associated with weakened abdominal muscles and instead is associated with urinary tract defects, cryptochordism, and a variety of genetic and environmental conditions which contribute to abdominal distention. In this image, the distention of the abdomen is readily apparent.</p>

<p>This is a 69 year male presenting with abdominal pain. He has history of end stage renal disease on hemodialysis. Upon questioning the patient, he admits to eating chalk. Geophagy (soil-eating) is a form of pica where individuals ingest earthy or soil like substances. Pica in the absence of mental disorder it is often reported in patients with anemia and mineral deficiency, most commonly in pregnant women and children.  Pica, particularly “ice pica” is commonly seen in dialysis patients. In this case, geophagy pica was the diagnosis.</p>

<p>This is a scan showing a patient who has situs inversus totalis, a rare congenital condition where the abdominal and thoracic organs develop in the reversed positions of their normal anatomy. This why organs such as the liver can be seen in the left side of the patient's abdominal cavity rather than the right. </p>

<p>It always amazes me how large tumors can grow inside our bodies.  When I first dissected the abdomen, I was amazed at how much "fit" in the abdominal pelvic cavity and it was hard to understand how there could be even more.  When we get to the repro block, we will discuss the anatomical changes associated with pregnancy - the fetus takes up a lot of room and the body has to accommodate.</p>

<p>Great image.  There is not contrast in the bladder, it is actually in the rectum.  The rectum, along with the stomach, are two places in the GI tract where contents can get "stored".  This is a distended rectum.  In lab you will see varius sizes of rectum depending on how much fecal contents where stored when the person died.</p>
<p>There is a case in lab - Table 16 I think - of a bowel perforation secondary to sigmoid diverticulitis.  </p>

<p>This is an anatomic variant, sometimes also called a "sliver of the liver".  It can wrap around the spleen and make the liver and spleen difficult to differentiate on scans.  It is an anatomic variant that most people never even know they have, but it can have some consequences - for example, it can be involved in blunt trauma and then mistaken for a splenic injury.</p>
